shortcut @cmd{N}, or the @buttontitle{New Reference} toolbar button.
Any of these commands will open an editor window with fields for various reference types.

@node Importing References
@section Importing References
@abstract{How to add existing references to a database.}

@cindex importing references

There are many ways to add existing reference items to a BibDesk database.
@itemize @bullet
@item @ref{Drag and Drop} or @ref{Copy and Paste} formatted text on the database window.
@item @ref{Drag and Drop} or @ref{Copy and Paste} formatted text files on the database window.
@item @ref{Drag and Drop} or @ref{Copy and Paste} files or URLs to link on the database window.
@item @ref{Drag and Drop} or @ref{Copy and Paste} on a detail editor window.
@item @ref{Drag and Drop}, @ref{Copy and Paste}, or @menutitle{Merge In} items from @ref{External Groups}.
@item Copy text to clipboard and choose @ref{Adding References From Text Sources, @menutitle{New Publications from Clipboard}}.
@item Choose @ref{Adding References From Text Sources, @menutitle{New Publications from File}} to import from a file.
@item Choose @ref{Adding References From Text Sources, @menutitle{New Publications from Web}} to import from a web source.
@item Select formatted text and choose @menutitle{Add to Bibliography} from @ref{Services, System Services}.
@item Open other file and @ref{Drag and Drop} or @ref{Copy and Paste} between database windows.
@item Choose @ref{Importing From Other Programs, @menutitle{Open Using Temporary Cite Keys}} to fix bibtex with missing cite keys.
@item Choose @ref{Opening a File, @menutitle{Open Using Filter}} to preprocess data.
@end itemize

Here @samp{formatted text} means bibliography data in any of a number of formats that BibDesk can recognize.
This includes BibTeX, RIS, Medline (PubMed), MARC, JSTOR, and ISI Web of Science. 

More details are given in the following sections.

