@node Grouping References
@section Grouping References
@abstract{Ways of grouping references in a database.}

@cindex group

@heading Grouping References

BibDesk offers a variety of ways to browse, organize, and search your bibliographic database.
BibDesk allows you to group references in a BibTeX file, similar to the way in which Apple
Mail allows you to group messages in folders, or iTunes in playlists.  
Field Groups, Smart Groups and Static Groups are the easiest way to keep a large file separated 
into distinct categories without managing many small files scattered around your hard drive.

@menu
* Field Groups::     Grouping references based on a particular field.
* Smart Groups::     Grouping references based on specific criteria.
* Static Groups::    Grouping arbitrary sets of references.
* External Groups::  Importing groups of items from an external source.
@end menu

@node Field Groups
@subsection Field Groups

@cindex field group

@subheading Features

Field Groups groups organize entries based on the contents of a certain field, 
the @samp{group field,} such as the @samp{Group} or @samp{Keywords} field.

In order to select a field to use as a group field, use the popup menu at the top of the list
on the left-hand side of BibDesk's window.  Add a BibTeX field name to this menu, or use one
of the existing options.  When you choose a group field from the popup menu, a list of all
possible groups is constructed, using the contents of the selected field for all entries in
your file.  

@subheading Example

Suppose you use the @samp{Keywords} field to group entries.  If you
have an entry with @samp{Keywords = @{models, constitutive relation, cohesion@}}
and another entry with @samp{Keywords = @{Models, constitutive, stress, cohesion@}},
your group list will show 6 groups: 
@samp{models, constitutive relation, cohesion, Models, constitutive, stress}.
A few points to note:  groups are case-sensitive, and partial matches are not accepted, and
one group (cohesion) will have two entries visible when it is selected in the group list.
Separators that are recognized for groups are @samp{;:,} and @samp{and}, at present.
@samp{and} will be ignored as separator when the entry contains any of the separator characters. 
The separator characters can be changed with a hidden preference using Terminal.app. 
To change it to, say, @samp{;,}, quit BibDesk and enter the following command in Terminal (exclude double quotes): 
``@code{defaults write edu.ucsd.cs.mmccrack.bibdesk BDSKGroupFieldSeparatorCharactersKey ';,'}''
then hit return.

You can add entries or files to a group via drag-and-drop by dragging the selected files to a
particular group's icon.  New items created in BibDesk are added to the presently selected group, 
but items dragged into the main publications list are not added to a group (think of the danger of
using @samp{Journal} as a group, and adding publications to that group!).

The default group separator is a semicolon followed by a single space @samp{; }, but this can be
changed with a hidden preference using Terminal.app.  To change the separator to a comma
followed by a single space, quit BibDesk and enter the following command in Terminal (exclude double quotes): 
``@code{defaults write edu.ucsd.cs.mmccrack.bibdesk BDSKDefaultGroupFieldSeparatorKey ', '}''
then hit return.

@subheading Editing

Field groups can be edited:  Changing the name of the group, will change the current value of
the current group field for all the items in the group.  In the case of authors, they will be matched 
using fuzzy logic, so be sure that you really want to change the author name for all items in the group!

For authors, you can get more info about the author using the command @menutitle{Get Info} 
(@cmd{I}) from the @menutitle{File} menu. 

Using the ``delete'' key to delete an item while a group is selected will result in the removal
of that item from the present group.  To delete the item from the database while a group is
selected, use @opt{}-delete.  To see the group equivalents for @menutitle{Edit} menu commands,
hold down the @opt{} key while the @menutitle{Edit} menu is displayed.

@node Smart Groups
@subsection Smart Groups

@cindex smart group
@kindex Option-Cmd-G
@kindex Cmd-I

BibDesk supports smart groups that dynamically change their content based on a list of
user-specified criteria.  To add a smart group, use the command @menutitle{New Smart Group} (@optcmd{G})
from the @menutitle{File} menu.  Additional search criteria can be added using the round ``+'' button,
and removed using the round ``-'' button, while the popup menu at the top of the panel can be used to
specify whether ``all'' or ``any'' of the additional criteria are matched.  This feature offers more flexible
searching than the standard Boolean quicksearch, and is always available.

The search criteria can later edit using thecommand @menutitle{Get Info} (@cmd{I}) in the @menutitle{File} menu, 
or in the contextual menhu for the group.  Its name can be changed after doubleclicking the group or 
choosing the appropriate contextual menu item. 

Smart groups are stored in the @samp{@@comment} field of your BibTeX file.  The format is that of a Mac OS X
XML property list, but you should @emph{not} modify the comment with a text editor, or rely on the format remaining
consistent across versions of BibDesk.  Some BibTeX editors may not preserve the contents of the @samp{@@comment}
field, unfortunately (early versions of BibDesk didn't preserve it, either).

Text-based fields are compared case-insensitively, for the criteria specified.  The BibDesk @samp{Date-Modified}
and @samp{Date-Created} fields are handled specially.  You can enter date ranges in various convenient ways.  
Date comparisons are automatically updated several times per day, so the relative comparison should
always be true.

@node Static Groups
@subsection Static Groups

@cindex static group
@kindex Control-Cmd-G

BibDesk supports static groups that contain an arbitrary set of items.  To add a static group, 
use the command @menutitle{New Static Group} (@ctrcmd{G}) from the @menutitle{File} menu.  
To add publications to the group, just drag the items and drop them on the group. 

@node External Groups
@subsection External Groups

@cindex external group

BibDesk can automatically fetch publications from external sources.  There are four types of external groups.  

Shared Groups contain items that others share on your local network.  
They are fetched using Bonjour.  This is similar to sharing of music files in iTunes.  
You can turn on sharing in the @ref{Sharing Preferences,Sharing Preferences}.  

External File Groups get their items from a remote URL on the internet or from a local file on your computer. 

Script Groups generate their items using a script, either a shell script or an AppleScript.  
For example, the script can download content from a remote location and parse the content to get the items.  
The script should return valid BibTeX. 

@ref{Searching External Databases, Search Groups} contain items obtained from searching an external database, 
such as PubMed or libraries allowing z39.50 searches. 

Items in external groups are not included in the Library and can not be edited.  
You can add external items to your Library by dragging them to the Library group.  
You can also use the @menutitle{Merge In External Publications} menu item in the 
@menutitle{File} menu. This wil only add items that are not yet in your Library. 

