@node Syntax for Z39.50 Searching
@section Syntax for Z39.50 Searching
@abstract{Syntax for searching z39.50 databases}

@cindex z39.50

To search a z39.50 database, simply enter one or more terms into the  
z39.50 search field:
@example
morgenthau politics
@end example
This will return all records that contain both @samp{morgenthau} and  
@samp{politics}. These search terms can appear in any field, 
and all the words are matched (each token is implicitly AND-ed.) 

To search for a phrase, put it in quotes:
@example
morgenthau "politics among"
@end example
To search in a particular field (see below for valid fields), enter a  
string of the following kind into the z39.50 search field:
@example
foo=SearchForMe
@end example
where @samp{foo} is an index specifying the fields of database records to
be searched, and @samp{SearchForMe} is the text string of interest. 

For example, a search for works written by Sewall Wright can be
conducted as follows:
@example
au="Wright, Sewall"
@end example
The indexes available in BibDesk are represented in the table
below. If a search supports relations, operators such as @samp{>}, @samp{<},
@samp{<>}, @samp{<=}, and @samp{>=} can be used, for instance, to search for works
published after a certain year. Note that, though the use of relations
is supported in BibDesk, many z39.50 servers do not support them.

For more information about MARC fields that are searched, consult OCLC's 
@uref{http://www.oclc.org/bibformats/default.htm,Bibliographic Formats and Standards} pages.

Boolean operators may be used to search several indexes at once, as in:
@example
au="Wright, Sewall" and ti="livestock breeding"
@end example
which will find works by Wright with the phrase @samp{livestock breeding}
in the title. When different indexes are used, Boolean operators must be included. 

