@node Syntax for Entrez Searching
@section Syntax for Entrez Searching
@abstract{Syntax for searching Entrez databases}

@cindex Entrez
@cindex Searching PubMed

Entrez databases use a search syntax closer to natural language than
does z39.50 databases. Enter key words, and the Entrez server will
generate a custom set of search results based on its retrieval
algorithms. Note that when searching PubMed for personal author  
names, @samp{,}
should not be entered between first names and last initials, and that
first initials (as opposed to first names) are typically used, as in
@samp{wright s} or @samp{fisher ra}.

For more focused searching, Entrez allows terms to be combined using
Boolean operators. According to the Entrez documentation, available at
@uref{http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/bv.fcgi?rid=helpentrez.section.EntrezHelp.Boolean_Operators,Boolean Operators},
these must be entered as follows.

@multitable {AND:} {}
@item @samp{AND:}
@tab Combine two search terms together to find all documents that contain BOTH terms.
@item @samp{OR:}
@tab Combine two search terms together to find all documents that contain EITHER term.
@item @samp{NOT:}
@tab Combine two search terms together to find all documents that contain search term 1 BUT NOT search term 2.
@end multitable

The Entrez search rules and syntax for using Boolean operators
are:
@itemize
@item Boolean operators AND, OR, NOT must be entered in UPPERCASE
(e.g., promoters OR response elements).
@item Entrez processes all Boolean operators in a left-to-right
sequence. The order in which Entrez processes a search statement can
be changed by enclosing individual concepts in parentheses. The terms
inside the parentheses are processed first as a unit and then
incorporated into the overall strategy. For example, the search
statement: @samp{g1p3 AND (response element OR promoter)} is processed by
Entrez by OR-ing the terms @samp{response element OR promoter} first and then
AND-ing the resulting set of @samp{documents with g1p3}.
@end itemize
Another way in which searches can be focused in PubMed is by the use
of extensions to the search terms. For instance, to search for @samp{random
genetic drift} in the MeSH terms field only, enter the following:
@example
random genetic drift [hm]
@end example
into the search field. Note that the extension appears in brackets
after the search key (@samp{random genetic drift,} in this case).

Other useful extensions include the following.

@multitable {lastau} {language (use the first three letters of the language's name, but not that "ja" means "japanese".)}
@headitem Extension @tab Meaning
@item au 
@tab Author
@item 1au 
@tab First author
@item lastau 
@tab Last author name
@item la 
@tab Language (use the first three letters of the language's name, but note that "ja" means "japanese".)
@item sh 
@tab MeSH Subheadings
@item dp 
@tab Publication date in YYYY/MM/DD format. Month and day are optional.
@item ti 
@tab Title
@item tiab 
@tab Title or abstract
@end multitable

Complete documentation of the extensions is provided at 
@uref{http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/bv.fcgi?rid=helppubmed.section.pubmedhelp.Search_Field_Descrip, Search Field Description and Tags}.

